We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms described suggest diphtheria, which is caused by the gram-positive club-shaped bacilli Corynebacterium diphtheriae. The most likely bacterial culture result is small black colonies on tellurite agar, which is the characteristic appearance of C. diphtheriae. Hemolytic black colonies on blood agar are seen in Streptococcus pyogenes, bluish green colonies on Loeffler’s serum is seen in Corynebacterium pseudotuberculosis, and greyish-white colonies on Thayer-Martin agar is seen in Neisseria gonorrhoeae.
